<div id="review_2056976795" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2056976795" />
    <a title="B. P. Rinehart" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4635205-b-p-rinehart"><img alt="B. P. Rinehart" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1347740735p2/4635205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2056976795?book_show_action=true">Mar 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="B. P. Rinehart" class="user" itemprop="url" name="B. P. Rinehart" href="/user/show/4635205-b-p-rinehart">B. P. Rinehart</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/10978496-devil-in-a-blue-dress">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4635205-b-p-rinehart?shelf=un-decade-african-descent">un-decade-african-descent</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4635205-b-p-rinehart?shelf=reading-in-a-time-of-corvid">reading-in-a-time-of-corvid</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2056976795" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1896469807979147045"><a href='https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SllhnR7D8LA' rel='nofollow noopener'>Good Rockin’ Tonight by Wyonnie Harris</a><br/><br/>&quot;<i>&apos;That&apos;s just like you, Easy. You learn stuff and you be thinkin&apos; like white men be thinkin&apos;. You be thikin&apos; that what&apos;s right fo&apos; them is right fo&apos; you. <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[She look like she white and you think like you white. But brother you don&apos;t know that you both poor niggers. <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> And a nigger ain&apos;t never gonna be happy &apos;less he accept what he is.&apos;</i>&quot;<br/><br/><br/>To start things off, it is amazing that it took so long for a character like Easy Rawlins to come a</span>
  <span id="freeText1896469807979147045" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SllhnR7D8LA" rel="nofollow noopener">Good Rockin’ Tonight by Wyonnie Harris</a><br /><br />"<i>'That's just like you, Easy. You learn stuff and you be thinkin' like white men be thinkin'. You be thikin' that what's right fo' them is right fo' you. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[She look like she white and you think like you white. But brother you don't know that you both poor niggers. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> And a nigger ain't never gonna be happy 'less he accept what he is.'</i>"<br /><br /><br />To start things off, it is amazing that it took so long for a character like Easy Rawlins to come along. To think that "crime noir" has existed as a genre for so long before we got a bonafide "homme noir" as a recurring protagonist. There have been many subversions/parodies of the crime noir/hard-boiled detective with black characters like the <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4392029.Chester_Himes" title="Chester Himes" rel="nofollow noopener">Chester Himes</a> novels and the comic book character Luke Cage (who was created during the blaxploitation-era), but Easy Rawlins is from a different old. He's from the same neighborhood, but took a different path.<br /><br />I've know of this story most of my life because I've always loved the movie adaptation of this novel that came out in 1995. Of course, the book gives you a more detailed world and it was interesting to see the extended backstory of the characters and Easy's though process. I liked that Mosley had a story to tell that was a little more than the mystery that is to be solved and that the book was commenting on more than plot. This book was a very masterful origin of the man who would become the detective. This is not the story of the man at full-strength as he spends the first-half of the book being the last one to know what's going on. After he starts to get the hang of things he advances the story to its conclusion and it feels well-earned.<br /><br />This is my third mystery novel read and is as well written as the last two I have read (even though I knew what the mystery was before I read the book). I really liked <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/20850.Walter_Mosley" title="Walter Mosley" rel="nofollow noopener">Walter Mosley</a>'s prose style a lot and again his world-building was master-class. He showed what <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/3567958.Isabel_Wilkerson" title="Isabel Wilkerson" rel="nofollow noopener">Isabel Wilkerson</a> showed in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8171378.The_Warmth_of_Other_Suns_The_Epic_Story_of_America_s_Great_Migration" title="The Warmth of Other Suns The Epic Story of America's Great Migration by Isabel Wilkerson" rel="nofollow noopener">The Warmth of Other Suns: The Epic Story of America's Great Migration</a> about how the tyrannical nature of the Jim Crow regime would lead almost an entire neighborhood of Houston Texas' Fifth Ward to transplant themselves to South-Central Los Angeles. This is a small world and a big one at the same time and this is the beginning of the exploration of it and all the dark, "noir" secrets that it holds.<br /><br /><br /><a href="https://youtu.be/HEyfT5PT9kE?t=22" rel="nofollow noopener">Softly as in a Morning Sunrise by John Coltrane feat. McCoy Tyner</a> - This song has nothing to do with the book, but Coltrane's long time pianist McCoy Tyner died the day I finished reading this book on March 6, 2020 so I'm just going to post this song that features a nice solo by him here.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1896469807979147045" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


